                                "start": 0,
                                "stop": 8.21,
                                "byte_start": 105472,
                                "byte_stop": 138386,
                                "text": "In case 08-538, Schwab versus Reilly, Justice Thomas has the opinion of the Court."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 8.21,
                        "stop": 347.794,
                        "byte_start": 138386,
                        "byte_stop": 0,
                        "speaker": {
                            "ID": 15100,
                            "name": "Clarence Thomas",
                            "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/people\/clarence_thomas",
                            "last_name": "Thomas",
                            "roles": [
                                {
                                    "id": 2744,
                                    "type": "scotus_justice",
                                    "date_start": 688194000,
                                    "date_end": 0,
                                    "appointing_president": "George H. W. Bush",
                                    "role_title": "Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "institution_name": "Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/preson_role\/scotus_justice\/2744"
                                }
                            ],
                            "thumbnail": {
                                "id": 32680,
                                "mime": "image\/png",
                                "size": 49064,
                                "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/sites\/default\/files\/clarence_thomas.png"
                            },
                            "length_of_service": 8870,
                            "identifier": "clarence_thomas"
                        },
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 8.21,
                                "stop": 14.789,
                                "byte_start": 138386,
                                "byte_stop": 164718,
                                "text": "This case comes to us on a Writ of Certiorari in the United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 14.789,
                                "stop": 21.953,
                                "byte_start": 164718,
                                "byte_stop": 193348,
                                "text": "Petitioner William Schwab is a trustee of respondent Reilly\u2019s Chapter 7 bankruptcy estate."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 21.953,
                                "stop": 26.957,
                                "byte_start": 193348,
                                "byte_stop": 213305,
                                "text": "Reilly filed for bankruptcy when her catering business failed."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 26.957,
                                "stop": 43.635,
                                "byte_start": 213305,
                                "byte_stop": 280074,
                                "text": "When a debtor files for bankruptcy, the bankruptcy code provides that, all of the debtor\u2019s assets become property of the bankruptcy estate, subject to the debtor\u2019s right to reclaim certain property as exempt."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 43.635,
                                "stop": 57.482,
                                "byte_start": 280074,
                                "byte_stop": 335454,
                                "text": "The bankruptcy code specifies the types of property debtors may exempt and also limits the value of the exemptions a debtor may claim in certain assets."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 57.482,
                                "stop": 71.964,
                                "byte_start": 335454,
                                "byte_stop": 393341,
                                "text": "Property a debtor claims as exempt, will be excluded from the bankruptcy estate unless a party in interest such as a trustee like Schwab objects to the exemption within a certain time period."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 71.964,
                                "stop": 82.444,
                                "byte_start": 393341,
                                "byte_stop": 435346,
                                "text": "In this case, we resolve the disagreement among the Courts of Appeals about what kind of information triggers the duty to file such an objection."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 82.444,
                                "stop": 90.324,
                                "byte_start": 435346,
                                "byte_stop": 466798,
                                "text": "Reilly\u2019s professional cooking equipment was one of the assets that became property of the bankruptcy estate."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 90.324,
                                "stop": 99.716,
                                "byte_start": 466798,
                                "byte_stop": 504414,
                                "text": "This equipment had sentimental and professional value to Reilly and quite understandably, she wished to exempt it."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 99.716,
                                "stop": 121.548,
                                "byte_start": 504414,
                                "byte_stop": 591768,
                                "text": "The bankruptcy code and rules require debtors who wish to exempt certain property, from their estates to fill out a form, that form is known as a Schedule C and on that form they must provide certain information about their exemption and the property to which the exemption applies."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 121.548,
                                "stop": 132.099,
                                "byte_start": 591768,
                                "byte_stop": 633877,
                                "text": "The dispute in this case arose because it is possible to read the information on Reilly\u0027s Schedule C form in one of two ways."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 132.099,
                                "stop": 162.992,
                                "byte_start": 633877,
                                "byte_stop": 757488,
                                "text": "Either as a claim to exempt the entire value of her cooking equipment which would be objectionable because the equipment\u0027s total value exceeds the dollar amount that the code allows for exemptions in such assets or it could be read as a claim to exempt only an interest in the equipment worth a certain dollar amount within the code\u2019s limits, which would then be proper and therefore unobjectionable."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 162.992,
                                "stop": 185.941,
                                "byte_start": 757488,
                                "byte_stop": 849335,
                                "text": "The bankruptcy code provisions that Reilly cited on her Schedule C, entitled her to exempt an interest in her cooking equipment, not to exceed a certain dollar amount because Reilly Schedule C expressly listed the value of the claimed exemption as a specific dollar amount below the code\u2019s limits."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 185.941,
                                "stop": 203.55,
                                "byte_start": 849335,
                                "byte_stop": 919761,
                                "text": "Schwab did not object to the exemption before he asked the bankruptcy Court for permission to sell the cooking equipment, so that he could pay Reilly the amount of her exemption and distribute the equipment\u0027s remaining value to Reilly\u2019s creditors."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 203.55,
                                "stop": 227.515,
                                "byte_start": 919761,
                                "byte_stop": 1015578,
                                "text": "Reilly object into the proposed sale on the grounds that Schwab should have read her Schedule as a claim to exempt the equipment in its entirety even though its appraised value exceeded the code\u2019s exempted limits."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 227.515,
                                "stop": 237.955,
                                "byte_start": 1015578,
                                "byte_stop": 1057374,
                                "text": "The District Court agreed with Reilly and held that Schwab\u2019s failure to make a timely objection entitled her to keep the equipment."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 237.955,
                                "stop": 251.938,
                                "byte_start": 1057374,
                                "byte_stop": 1113276,
                                "text": "Court of Appeals affirmed citing this Court\u2019s 1991 decision in Taylor versus Freeland, that the deadline for bankruptcy objections must be strictly enforced."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 251.938,
                                "stop": 278.379,
                                "byte_start": 1113276,
                                "byte_stop": 1219020,
                                "text": "In an opinion on file with the clerk today we reverse the judgment of the Court of Appeals, a better Schedule C entries must be read in light of the code, the bankruptcy code provisions that govern the exemptions set forth in the Schedule and code\u2019s requirement must control over a debtor\u2019s intent or a standalone reading of the Schedule."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 278.379,
                                "stop": 305.983,
                                "byte_start": 1219020,
                                "byte_stop": 1329465,
                                "text": "In this case, the code provisions that govern Reilly\u2019s exemptions define the property that she claimed exempt as an interest in her cooking equipment, not as a equipment itself, and place a specific dollar limit on the value of that interest because the dollar value Reilly assigned the interest on Schedule C was below the code\u2019s specified limits."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 305.983,
                                "stop": 340.518,
                                "byte_start": 1329465,
                                "byte_stop": 1467601,
                                "text": "Schwab was entitled to treat her claim as a valid exemption in the amount she listed and thus did not have to object to the claim, in order to preserve for the estate, the value in the equipment beyond that amount because Reilly\u2019s claimed the exemption in the equipment was not objectionable, neither Bankruptcy Rule 4003\u2019s deadline for making objections, nor our Taylor decision, if in enforcing that deadline applies here."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 340.518,
                                "stop": 347.794,
                                "byte_start": 1467601,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Justice Ginsburg has filed a dissenting opinion in which the Chief Justice and Justice Breyer have joined."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
